5|$|In 1907, Einstein {{was still}} eight {{years away from}} {{completing}} the general theory <b>of</b> <b>relativity.</b> Nonetheless, {{he was able to}} make a number of novel, testable predictions that were based on his starting point for developing his new theory: the equivalence principle.|$|E
5|$|In {{the early}} 20th century, {{physicists}} and mathematicians including Albert Einstein and Hermann Minkowski pioneered {{the use of}} four-dimensional geometry for describing the physical world. These efforts culminated {{in the formulation of}} Einstein's general theory <b>of</b> <b>relativity,</b> which relates gravity to the geometry of four-dimensional spacetime.|$|E
